  Key MOC Features (from the code)

  1. Hierarchical Sections: MOCSection with nested subsections
  2. Content Aggregation: Links to KUs, LPs, and Principles
  3. Cross-Domain Bridges: Connect related content across domains
  4. Practice Integration: Each section can recommend Habits, Tasks, Events
  5. Templates: MOCs can be templates that others copy
  6. Discovery: Find MOCs by shared content, domain, or tags

  Graph Relationships

  // MOC Structure
  (moc:MOC)-[:HAS_SECTION]->(section:MOCSection)
  (section)-[:HAS_SUBSECTION]->(subsection:MOCSection)

  // Content Organization
  (moc)-[:HAS_TOP_LEVEL_KNOWLEDGE]->(ku:Ku)
  (section)-[:CONTAINS_KNOWLEDGE]->(ku:Ku)
  (section)-[:CONTAINS_PATH]->(lp:Lp)
  (section)-[:CONTAINS_PRINCIPLE]->(principle:Principle)

  // Cross-Domain Bridges
  (moc)-[:BRIDGES_TO {domain: "ml"}]->(ku:Ku)

  // Practice Recommendations
  (section)-[:RECOMMENDS_HABIT]->(habit:Habit)
  (section)-[:RECOMMENDS_TASK]->(task:Task)

  // MOC Discovery
  (moc)-[:RELATED_TO_MOC]->(other_moc:MOC)

  MOC's Role in the 14-Domain Architecture

  MOC belongs in Content/Organization Domains because it:
  - Organizes knowledge (doesn't create new knowledge)
  - Provides navigation (meta-layer over KU/LS/LP)
  - Enables discovery (find related content)
  - Bridges domains (connects cross-domain content)

  The three Content/Organization domains work together:
  - Journals = Input processing (text → structured activities)
  - Assignments = User interface for submissions
  - MOC = Knowledge organization and navigation

  Should MOC Stay in the Architecture?

  Yes, MOC serves a distinct purpose:

  | Without MOC                                | With MOC                               |
  |--------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------|
  | Knowledge only accessible via linear paths | Knowledge browsable by topic           |
  | No cross-domain navigation                 | Cross-domain bridges enabled           |
  | No personalized knowledge dashboards       | Users create their own knowledge maps  |
  | Discovery limited to search                | Contextual discovery via relationships |

